@startuml
' Author: Nicholas Irvine  GitHub https://github.com/SaladStik  LinkedIn https://www.linkedin.com/in/nicholas-irvine-303ab5284/
title Orbit One Job Life Through the Event Queue

' The event queue explainer. Follow a single job from click to done and
' learn the Kafka words along the way. Producer, consumer, topic,
' partition, consumer group, offsets, at least once delivery.

[*] --> Accepted : UI POST /api/jobs, gateway writes the row
note right of Accepted : In the database, not on the queue yet. If the publish fails it stays here.

Accepted --> Queued : gateway PRODUCES to job.requests, then marks it queued
note right of Queued : The gateway is the producer. The topic is an ordered durable log. The producer does not block.

Queued --> Processing : python-worker CONSUMES\nthe event
note right of Processing : In a consumer group each member gets one partition, so workers scale out.

Processing --> Completed : worker UPDATEs the row\nstatus 'queued' -> 'completed'
note right of Completed : Commit the offset after the work. A crash means redelivery, so deliver at least once. Be idempotent.

Completed --> Captured : Debezium PRODUCES CDC event\nto orbit.public.jobs
note right of Captured : Debezium is a second producer with the same queue mechanics.

Captured --> Delivered : node-gateway CONSUMES CDC\nand pushes over WebSocket
Delivered --> [*] : UI shows the result

note left of Queued : A queue here is an append only log. Events are not deleted on read.

note bottom : The history is durable. Each state is a Postgres row by owner. On a later\nlogin the UI reads it back, so jobs that finished while you were away still show.

@enduml
